gene-development.page_content: The Great Attractor is a gravitational anomaly in intergalactic space that reveals the presence of a huge concentration of mass, pulling galaxies, including our own Milky Way, toward it.
Despite its immense influence, the exact nature and mass of the Great Attractor remain mysterious due to its location behind the Zone of Avoidance â€” a region blocked by the Milky Way's disk.
Black holes represent the ultimate collapse of matter into an infinitely dense point. The curvature of space-time becomes infinite at the singularity, where classical physics breaks down.
Quantum effects around black holes suggest that information may not be entirely lost. This unresolved paradox has sparked debates in physics for decades.
The Great Attractor lies roughly 250 million light-years away in the direction of the Centaurus and Hydra constellations. Its influence suggests a massive hidden structure.
Some theories suggest that the matter within the Great Attractor could be part of an even larger structure known as the Laniakea Supercluster, redefining our understanding of the cosmic web.
